1
00:00:13,040 --> 00:00:14,300
Like, right here?

2
00:00:14,330 --> 00:00:16,300
Mmm, no. Move, move.

3
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:18,419
[IKE] <i>Everything you always
wanted to know about the party</i>

4
00:00:18,420 --> 00:00:20,187
<i>but were afraid to ask.</i>

5
00:00:20,270 --> 00:00:24,024
<i>Question: Ike, you never write.
Why are you writing to me?</i>

6
00:00:24,107 --> 00:00:26,652
<i>Answer: To save the date.</i>

7
00:00:26,690 --> 00:00:28,600
<i>Question: What date?</i>

8
00:00:28,620 --> 00:00:32,031
<i>Answer: Saturday, July 6, 1991.</i>

9
00:00:32,110 --> 00:00:33,120
[BLOWING]

10
00:00:33,140 --> 00:00:35,140
<i>Question: What am I saving it for?</i>

11
00:00:35,170 --> 00:00:37,788
- <i>Answer: A summer party.</i>
- [MUTTERS]

12
00:00:38,900 --> 00:00:40,720
<i>Question: What should I wear?</i>

13
00:00:40,940 --> 00:00:43,540
<i>Answer: The party is safari themed,</i>

14
00:00:43,560 --> 00:00:46,672
<i>so dress like the wild
exotic animal that you are.</i>

15
00:00:48,006 --> 00:00:49,842
<i>Question: But how will I get there?</i>

16
00:00:50,340 --> 00:00:54,130
<i>Answer: Meet on the southwest
corner of 40th and 8th Avenue.</i>

17
00:00:54,150 --> 00:00:55,680
<i>Don't worry about the ride home.</i>

18
00:00:55,700 --> 00:00:58,934
<i>You'll be dropped off at the
very same spot at 10:00 p.m.,</i>

19
00:00:59,017 --> 00:01:00,685
<i>tanned, tired and tipsy.</i>

20
00:01:00,686 --> 00:01:03,021
- This is the bus to Ike's party?
- It sure is.

21
00:01:03,105 --> 00:01:04,105
Okay, yeah. [CHUCKLES]

22
00:01:04,120 --> 00:01:06,191
[IKE] <i>Question: What are
we gonna do at the party?</i>

23
00:01:06,210 --> 00:01:08,250
<i>Answer: What aren't we going to do?</i>

24
00:01:08,280 --> 00:01:09,820
<i>There'll be swimming, chicken fights,</i>

25
00:01:09,830 --> 00:01:12,320
<i>Ping-Pong, lawn darts, croquet, limbo</i>

26
00:01:12,322 --> 00:01:13,657
<i>and so much more.</i>

27
00:01:13,740 --> 00:01:15,325
- [HORNS HONKING]
- <i>See you soon.</i>

28
00:01:15,970 --> 00:01:19,900
- Synced & corrected by<font color="#E83286"> MementMori </font>-
-- <font color="#138CE9">www.addic7ed.com</font> --

29
00:01:31,175 --> 00:01:34,136
[SNIFFING]

30
00:01:39,520 --> 00:01:42,390
Marty, what is that odor
that smells like shit

31
00:01:42,477 --> 00:01:43,569
by the lounge chairs?

32
00:01:43,570 --> 00:01:46,080
Well, i-it is what it smells like.

33
00:01:46,100 --> 00:01:47,732
I think the septic tank is backed up.

34
00:01:47,733 --> 00:01:50,068
[SIGHS] Can you do something
about it, please?

35
00:01:50,152 --> 00:01:51,540
I know it's a safari party,

36
00:01:51,560 --> 00:01:53,321
but I don't want it to
smell like elephant dung.

37
00:01:53,322 --> 00:01:55,490
- [MARTY] Okay.
- Whoa, whoa, whoa. Not so fast.

38
00:01:55,570 --> 00:01:57,780
Seriously, Bonnie? Two-pieces?

39
00:01:57,800 --> 00:02:00,287
They're children. This isn't Cambodia.

40
00:02:00,780 --> 00:02:03,290
- Can you go change, please?
- Come on, girls. Come on.

41
00:02:03,373 --> 00:02:04,458
Hold on. Wait.

42
00:02:04,860 --> 00:02:06,330
Is that what you're wearing?

43
00:02:06,350 --> 00:02:08,461
Yeah. [STAMMERS] Is it too much?

44
00:02:09,120 --> 00:02:11,420
It's fine. It's fine.
Just put them in dresses.

45
00:02:11,507 --> 00:02:12,508
Okay. Okay.

46
00:02:12,800 --> 00:02:14,425
Dr. Ike, everything okay?

47
00:02:14,426 --> 00:02:16,720
Yeah, I'm just... [SIGHS]

48
00:02:17,700 --> 00:02:20,220
What if this party isn't as
fun as Stephen Baldwin's?

49
00:02:20,307 --> 00:02:21,934
Stephen Baldwin put on a party

50
00:02:22,017 --> 00:02:24,311
that people are gonna talk
about for a long time.

51
00:02:24,320 --> 00:02:25,650
That's a given.

52
00:02:25,670 --> 00:02:28,900
However, look at this
attention to detail.

53
00:02:28,920 --> 00:02:30,567
This is gonna be a great party.

54
00:02:30,980 --> 00:02:32,310
[IKE] I don't know.

55
00:02:32,780 --> 00:02:34,070
What if no one shows

56
00:02:34,090 --> 00:02:37,574
and it's just you and me and a
hundred pounds of chopped meat?

57
00:02:37,658 --> 00:02:39,326
Still sounds fun to me.

58
00:02:39,910 --> 00:02:42,538
["PARTY UP" PLAYING]

59
00:02:47,660 --> 00:02:49,752
Let the good times roll! Welcome!

60
00:02:49,753 --> 00:02:52,380
- You are the man.
- No, you. Stop it. Stop it.

61
00:02:52,381 --> 00:02:53,589
- How are you?
- Hey, Ike.

62
00:02:53,590 --> 00:02:54,591
- What's up, David?
- Ike.

63
00:02:54,610 --> 00:02:56,260
- Hi, Miriam.
- [LAUGHING] Ike.

64
00:02:56,343 --> 00:02:58,094
So happy you made it. I love your hat.

65
00:02:58,095 --> 00:03:00,472
Yeah. Oh. I have something for you.

66
00:03:00,556 --> 00:03:03,517
- [WOMAN] Whoo-hoo! Party time.
- Thank you so much. Hey!

67
00:03:04,184 --> 00:03:06,936
You know, this is the same strength
as my mother's reading glasses.

68
00:03:06,937 --> 00:03:09,188
- Do you have them in a bifocal?
- [LAUGHING] Yeah.

69
00:03:09,189 --> 00:03:11,275
- Get in there, Miriam. Have fun.
- Okay. [GIGGLES]

70
00:03:11,358 --> 00:03:12,984
Hi, Iz. How are you?

71
00:03:12,985 --> 00:03:15,445
By the way, we're putting in
a hot tub right over here.

72
00:03:15,470 --> 00:03:17,656
We have porcelain tile
flying in from Murano.

73
00:03:17,670 --> 00:03:20,157
The Italians, they do it so
much better. Am I right?

74
00:03:20,158 --> 00:03:21,576
We bought the place next door too.

75
00:03:21,577 --> 00:03:23,036
- Ooh.
- We're totally refurbishing.

76
00:03:23,070 --> 00:03:25,330
Putting in a golf course, a tennis court

77
00:03:25,350 --> 00:03:27,291
and a sundial.

78
00:03:27,370 --> 00:03:29,299
- You and Bonnie have real vision.
- You know Bonnie.

79
00:03:29,300 --> 00:03:30,340
She loves a project.

80
00:03:30,377 --> 00:03:31,712
- Mmm.
- It's why she married me.

81
00:03:31,795 --> 00:03:32,921
[BOTH LAUGHING]

82
00:03:33,005 --> 00:03:35,174
Thank you for coming.
It's great to see you.

83
00:03:36,800 --> 00:03:38,468
Let's touch base on Monday.

84
00:03:39,094 --> 00:03:41,638
There may be a spot opening
up on the synagogue board

85
00:03:41,680 --> 00:03:43,473
that I think you'd be perfect for.

86
00:03:44,975 --> 00:03:47,393
- [MOUTHING] Yep.
- [CHUCKLES] All right.

87
00:03:47,394 --> 00:03:49,646
- [SONG CONTINUES ON SPEAKERS, MUFFLED]
- [SIGHS]

88
00:03:50,480 --> 00:03:51,481
- [GASPS] Marty.
- Huh?

89
00:03:51,565 --> 00:03:52,649
- We're a hit.
- [CHUCKLES]

90
00:03:52,730 --> 00:03:54,560
I think people are having a great time.

91
00:03:54,580 --> 00:03:56,235
- Mm-hmm.
- What a team we make, huh?

92
00:03:56,236 --> 00:03:59,405
I was thinking I should put some
dip out. I forgot all about dip.

93
00:03:59,406 --> 00:04:00,532
Who doesn't love dip?

94
00:04:01,040 --> 00:04:03,240
But I don't want you cooking all day.

95
00:04:03,327 --> 00:04:05,954
You know, I want you to
relax and enjoy yourself.

96
00:04:06,038 --> 00:04:07,269
I like cooking. Cooking is good.

97
00:04:07,270 --> 00:04:09,166
Whatever you say, chief. [CHUCKLES]

98
00:04:09,500 --> 00:04:10,700
Oh, by the way.

99
00:04:10,792 --> 00:04:11,877
I was thinking.

100
00:04:11,900 --> 00:04:14,296
Maybe I can put the,
uh, barbecue back a bit

101
00:04:14,300 --> 00:04:16,130
and give you a little more room.

102
00:04:16,150 --> 00:04:18,257
I don't want people
breathing down your neck.

103
00:04:18,341 --> 00:04:20,426
They can't be disturbing
the genius at work.

104
00:04:20,427 --> 00:04:22,850
[CHUCKLES] No. It's a good idea.

105
00:04:22,870 --> 00:04:24,515
Yeah. Yeah, a little space.

106
00:04:24,598 --> 00:04:27,278
Okay. I'm gonna make sure everyone's
good on drinks. [CLICKS TONGUE]

107
00:04:27,351 --> 00:04:29,561
And I said, "I don't care
if it is before Labor Day.

108
00:04:29,580 --> 00:04:32,147
You'll never see these
legs in white pants."

109
00:04:32,231 --> 00:04:34,274
[WOMEN LAUGH]

110
00:04:34,858 --> 00:04:36,944
- [MARTY] There you go.
- [WOMAN] Thanks.

111
00:04:40,240 --> 00:04:41,280
[IKE] That was way out.

112
00:04:42,866 --> 00:04:45,035
- Hey!
- Hi, Ike!

113
00:04:46,060 --> 00:04:48,240
- What?
- Nothing.

114
00:04:48,330 --> 00:04:49,748
- Do you need me?
- No.

115
00:04:52,417 --> 00:04:53,502
Hey!

116
00:04:56,171 --> 00:04:58,298
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

117
00:05:11,144 --> 00:05:13,564
[BOTTLES CLINK]

118
00:05:17,276 --> 00:05:19,819
If you let them walk all over you,
you know what they're gonna do.

119
00:05:19,820 --> 00:05:21,720
- Walk all over me. Yeah.
- That's right.

120
00:05:21,740 --> 00:05:24,150
This "buy a cake for
their birthday" tradition

121
00:05:24,170 --> 00:05:25,530
has gotten out of hand.

122
00:05:25,534 --> 00:05:26,994
Did you hear Cathy?

123
00:05:27,010 --> 00:05:29,079
"Red velvet for me. Red velvet."

124
00:05:29,100 --> 00:05:30,414
Please, you know.

125
00:05:30,420 --> 00:05:32,456
You're not running a bakery,
Marty. It's a business.

126
00:05:32,457 --> 00:05:35,335
No, I know, I know. Cathy can get
outta control with that stuff.

127
00:05:39,240 --> 00:05:40,380
So...

128
00:05:41,740 --> 00:05:43,130
That was pretty epic, huh?

129
00:05:43,218 --> 00:05:44,219
[CHUCKLES]

130
00:05:44,860 --> 00:05:46,800
- What was epic?
- The party, Marty.

131
00:05:46,810 --> 00:05:48,390
- Oh. Yeah.
- Yeah?

132
00:05:48,400 --> 00:05:50,580
Right, I mean, it was a lot of work.

133
00:05:51,260 --> 00:05:54,100
- But yeah.
- We should fix the lighting by the pool.

134
00:05:54,120 --> 00:05:56,080
Man, by eight o'clock,
it was pitch black.

135
00:05:56,110 --> 00:05:58,024
I feel like I tore my rotator cuff

136
00:05:58,025 --> 00:06:00,485
schlepping all those wet
towels to and from the dryer.

137
00:06:00,569 --> 00:06:02,196
People loved the pool. They loved it.

138
00:06:02,220 --> 00:06:04,031
I opened so many bottles of soda pop,

139
00:06:04,114 --> 00:06:06,420
I... I haven't been able
to make a solid fist.

140
00:06:06,450 --> 00:06:08,826
We... You know, we could hang
string lights the next time.

141
00:06:08,827 --> 00:06:09,953
Next time?

142
00:06:10,280 --> 00:06:11,490
Mmm.

143
00:06:11,900 --> 00:06:13,950
- There's gonna be a next time?
- Of course.

144
00:06:15,000 --> 00:06:16,459
Ma... We're just getting started.

145
00:06:16,460 --> 00:06:17,711
Oh.

146
00:06:17,720 --> 00:06:19,129
Wha... Marty. [STAMMERS]

147
00:06:19,213 --> 00:06:21,298
- These parties are great for us.
- Uh-huh.

148
00:06:21,381 --> 00:06:24,050
They're great for business.
They're great for networking.

149
00:06:24,051 --> 00:06:25,385
- [MARTY CHUCKLES]
- Mmm?

150
00:06:25,469 --> 00:06:27,804
[INHALES SHARPLY]
Why? You didn't enjoy it?

151
00:06:27,820 --> 00:06:29,097
No, I... I liked it. Yeah.

152
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:30,516
It was good. Yeah, I guess.

153
00:06:31,160 --> 00:06:33,100
What is it? What's bothering you?

154
00:06:33,185 --> 00:06:35,229
- I'm not much of a party guy.
- Oh.

155
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:37,940
I... I didn't know anyone there.

156
00:06:37,960 --> 00:06:39,419
I-I-I didn't know what to say to anyone.

157
00:06:39,420 --> 00:06:42,653
I think this is a narrative
you tell yourself, hmm?

158
00:06:42,670 --> 00:06:44,100
I've seen you party, Marty.

159
00:06:44,112 --> 00:06:47,241
And I don't know how to tell
you this, but you're pretty fun.

160
00:06:47,324 --> 00:06:48,330
[CHUCKLES]

161
00:06:48,340 --> 00:06:50,160
No. No, I'm not fun.

162
00:06:51,620 --> 00:06:54,370
All right, well, I have an idea.

163
00:06:54,456 --> 00:06:56,480
Why don't we run it back?

164
00:06:56,500 --> 00:06:57,750
We'll have a second party,

165
00:06:57,751 --> 00:07:01,839
and we can use it as an opportunity
for you to make some connections.

166
00:07:01,880 --> 00:07:03,173
Hmm?

167
00:07:03,190 --> 00:07:06,300
There were some fantastic
people there, Marty. Fantastic.

168
00:07:06,301 --> 00:07:08,095
I'm just too shy.

169
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:11,472
- Oh, stop it already with the "shy."
- And... No.

170
00:07:11,473 --> 00:07:14,351
I'm going to help you
learn to enjoy yourself.

171
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:18,560
Okay? How's that sound?

172
00:07:19,380 --> 00:07:21,810
- Uh, what is that shake?
- [STAMMERS]

173
00:07:21,850 --> 00:07:23,485
- All right.
- Yeah?

174
00:07:23,569 --> 00:07:25,988
- Yes. Yeah. Yeah, yeah.
- All right. Okay. Good.

175
00:07:26,980 --> 00:07:28,860
By the way,

176
00:07:28,890 --> 00:07:30,324
I got you a little something.

177
00:07:30,325 --> 00:07:31,702
Huh.

178
00:07:35,380 --> 00:07:36,400
Wow.

179
00:07:37,900 --> 00:07:40,080
- A fish.
- A koi to be exact.

180
00:07:40,100 --> 00:07:42,296
- Well, thank you.
- You're welcome.

181
00:07:43,480 --> 00:07:46,466
- What do I do with it?
- I'm sure you'll figure it out.

182
00:07:49,320 --> 00:07:51,090
I guess we could build a pond.

183
00:07:51,180 --> 00:07:52,431
You know, in the Hamptons.

184
00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:56,640
That's a great idea.
That is a great idea.

185
00:07:56,727 --> 00:07:58,979
- Oh. [CHUCKLES]
- That might be a good project for you.

186
00:07:59,062 --> 00:08:00,856
- Thank you.
- Don't mention it.

187
00:08:01,607 --> 00:08:03,192
Well, okay.

188
00:08:03,275 --> 00:08:05,995
- He's looking right at me. [CHUCKLES]
- He is. I think he likes you.

189
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:07,988
- Yeah. I hope so.
- [CHUCKLES]

190
00:08:44,940 --> 00:08:47,270
Okay, play nice, guys.

191
00:08:47,300 --> 00:08:49,029
Adam, behave yourself.

192
00:09:01,124 --> 00:09:03,460
[CHATTERING, LAUGHING]

193
00:09:08,860 --> 00:09:10,890
- Take it easy with the <i>cervezas</i>.
- [LAUGHING]

194
00:09:10,910 --> 00:09:14,000
Sorry. [LAUGHS] I'm kidding.
Enjoy the <i>fiesta</i>, amigos.

195
00:09:14,020 --> 00:09:16,223
- [LAUGHS] Aw, <i>gracias</i>. Gracias.
- [WOMAN LAUGHING] Oh, yeah. Whoo.

196
00:09:16,224 --> 00:09:18,975
- So was I.
- Oh, Miriam. I see you've met Noreen.

197
00:09:18,976 --> 00:09:20,143
Yes. Yes.

198
00:09:20,170 --> 00:09:23,849
Terrific. Well, as they say in Oaxaca...

199
00:09:23,850 --> 00:09:25,232
- Lehayim.
- [WOMEN CHUCKLING]

200
00:09:25,315 --> 00:09:26,358
Cheers.

201
00:09:27,420 --> 00:09:29,060
Mmm. [SMACKS LIPS]

202
00:09:29,100 --> 00:09:31,822
I see our, uh, chef is hard at work.

203
00:09:32,650 --> 00:09:33,900
Oh, yeah.

204
00:09:34,366 --> 00:09:35,784
He seems nice. [CHUCKLES]

205
00:09:35,868 --> 00:09:37,077
Oh, Marty.

206
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:39,490
He's a little shy, but...

207
00:09:39,580 --> 00:09:40,622
Oh.

208
00:09:41,540 --> 00:09:45,711
Well, don't let me hold you back.
If you, you know, would like to...

209
00:09:45,794 --> 00:09:48,172
- Yeah, I'll go. I'll go talk to him.
- Hmm.

210
00:09:48,200 --> 00:09:49,423
Okay. [CHUCKLES]

211
00:09:53,100 --> 00:09:55,790
- [MIRIAM] The grill master himself.
- [MARTY] Oh. [CHUCKLES]

212
00:09:55,810 --> 00:09:57,139
Who? Me?

213
00:09:58,682 --> 00:10:01,435
- Oh. Miriam.
- Oh, right. Of course.

214
00:10:01,518 --> 00:10:03,645
- Yeah. From, uh, shiva.
- Yes.

215
00:10:03,729 --> 00:10:06,982
- And, uh, Ike's waiting room, right?
- [LAUGHS] That too.

216
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:10,110
Well, Ike said that
you are the best cook.

217
00:10:10,120 --> 00:10:13,488
I'm gonna need that, uh,
kebab recipe one of these days.

218
00:10:13,572 --> 00:10:15,991
Well, the trick is to
oil the skewers first.

219
00:10:16,400 --> 00:10:18,460
Then the meat cooks from the inside out.

220
00:10:18,480 --> 00:10:19,577
Ah. [CHUCKLES]

221
00:10:19,578 --> 00:10:21,038
I'm boring myself now.

222
00:10:21,121 --> 00:10:22,998
No! No, no. No.

223
00:10:23,460 --> 00:10:25,120
Interesting. [CHUCKLES]

224
00:10:26,740 --> 00:10:30,088
So, uh, did you tell your
mother no about Florida?

225
00:10:31,700 --> 00:10:34,710
Wow, you have, um... You have
a great memory. [CHUCKLES]

226
00:10:34,750 --> 00:10:37,429
I'm so sorry. I-I-I shouldn't have...

227
00:10:37,440 --> 00:10:39,097
No! No, no, no. No, it's fine.

228
00:10:39,181 --> 00:10:41,099
There's a few of us here, right?

229
00:10:42,380 --> 00:10:44,310
- Have you met Jennifer?
- No.

230
00:10:44,394 --> 00:10:45,604
She's some kind of heiress.

231
00:10:45,687 --> 00:10:48,087
On the board of the New York
City Ballet. That kind of thing.

232
00:10:48,106 --> 00:10:50,359
- Anyway, she's been with Ike forever.
- Huh.

233
00:10:50,442 --> 00:10:53,736
You must also know about one of
Ike's, uh, movie-star patients?

234
00:10:53,737 --> 00:10:55,197
Uh, I don't think so.

235
00:10:55,940 --> 00:10:57,820
- Okay, I shouldn't say. [CHUCKLES]
- Okay.

236
00:10:57,824 --> 00:10:59,659
Her name rhymes with "Myneth Maltrow."

237
00:10:59,660 --> 00:11:02,454
He did mention that, yes. Uh-huh.

238
00:11:02,500 --> 00:11:05,123
- It's quite a tribe, I guess.
- Yeah, yeah.

239
00:11:07,220 --> 00:11:09,877
[SIGHS] I-I should
get, uh, another tray.

240
00:11:09,878 --> 00:11:11,672
- Um...
- Oh.

241
00:11:11,690 --> 00:11:14,883
- Now I know how Julia Childs feels.
- Oh. [CHUCKLES]

242
00:11:14,900 --> 00:11:17,219
Minus the funny accent and the, uh...

243
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:18,762
th-the... the fulsome breasts.

244
00:11:18,846 --> 00:11:20,806
[LAUGHS]

245
00:11:21,380 --> 00:11:22,400
Huh.

246
00:11:22,420 --> 00:11:27,020
Who would have known that the lamb
kebabs are the number one hit?

247
00:11:27,040 --> 00:11:28,060
Hmm.

248
00:11:28,080 --> 00:11:31,108
I think it's the, uh,
cilantro I... I put on it.

249
00:11:31,191 --> 00:11:33,026
Oh. [CHUCKLES]

250
00:11:33,040 --> 00:11:35,940
So-Sorry. Do you know where
the bathroom is? [CHUCKLES]

251
00:11:35,960 --> 00:11:38,073
Uh... Yes, absolutely.

252
00:11:38,090 --> 00:11:40,867
It's, uh... It's down the hall,
second door on your left.

253
00:11:40,868 --> 00:11:42,560
It's a slow flush.

254
00:11:42,580 --> 00:11:44,490
Thank you for the heads-up.

255
00:11:44,580 --> 00:11:46,164
- [CHUCKLES]
- Mm-hmm.

256
00:11:46,248 --> 00:11:48,550
Oh. Is that Farrah Fawcett?

257
00:11:48,580 --> 00:11:50,502
It is. Cool, right?

258
00:11:50,586 --> 00:11:52,337
He met her on a flight to Tampa.

259
00:11:52,360 --> 00:11:54,631
- Oh, wow.
- Yeah, she's very lovely.

260
00:11:54,715 --> 00:11:57,425
[CHUCKLES] Oh, my gosh.

261
00:11:57,426 --> 00:11:59,803
Ike was such a sweet little boy.

262
00:11:59,887 --> 00:12:02,722
Uh, actually, that's me.

263
00:12:03,020 --> 00:12:04,640
With my parents and sister.

264
00:12:04,680 --> 00:12:05,809
- Really?
- Uh-huh.

265
00:12:06,435 --> 00:12:08,728
Huh. S-So, you knew Ike as a kid.

266
00:12:08,729 --> 00:12:09,855
Um...

267
00:12:10,397 --> 00:12:12,191
So you two are related.

268
00:12:12,274 --> 00:12:13,442
N-Not exactly.

269
00:12:14,700 --> 00:12:16,150
But...

270
00:12:16,236 --> 00:12:18,822
Y-You live here with Ike and Bonnie?

271
00:12:18,906 --> 00:12:21,366
Yeah. Yeah. Yeah, yeah.

272
00:12:21,400 --> 00:12:24,786
- [CHUCKLES] It is such a great home.
- Mmm.

273
00:12:24,870 --> 00:12:27,413
How long have the Herschkopfs
had it? Do you know?

274
00:12:27,414 --> 00:12:31,043
Um... Well, truth be told,

275
00:12:31,060 --> 00:12:33,160
it's... it's my family's home

276
00:12:33,180 --> 00:12:35,505
since... since the '50s, I guess. Yeah.

277
00:12:35,510 --> 00:12:37,174
A lot of happy memories.

278
00:12:37,190 --> 00:12:39,510
- Oh. Your family.
- Yeah. Yeah, yeah, yeah.

279
00:12:39,593 --> 00:12:41,219
Wait. This is your home?

280
00:12:41,800 --> 00:12:43,840
Well, I... I mean, it's our home.

281
00:12:44,460 --> 00:12:46,933
Uh, yeah, there's a name on the paper.

282
00:12:46,934 --> 00:12:48,929
But you know, it still takes
that special someone

283
00:12:48,930 --> 00:12:50,280
to figure out what it could be,

284
00:12:50,300 --> 00:12:52,606
and th-that's Ike... and Bonnie.

285
00:12:53,160 --> 00:12:55,350
I'm just good at executing ideas.

286
00:12:55,442 --> 00:12:57,986
So it's... it's... It's
a real team effort.

287
00:12:59,860 --> 00:13:02,110
- [CHUCKLES]
- Yeah.

288
00:13:02,199 --> 00:13:03,533
But that's interesting.

289
00:13:03,534 --> 00:13:06,537
- [CHUCKLES] Um, the left, second door?
- Yeah, left, second door.

290
00:13:06,580 --> 00:13:09,623
- Okay. You got it.
- Keep your hand on the... the lever.

291
00:13:10,958 --> 00:13:11,959
[DOOR CLOSES]

292
00:13:22,680 --> 00:13:23,880
So...

293
00:13:25,340 --> 00:13:27,010
can I ask you a question?

294
00:13:27,560 --> 00:13:28,800
Absolutely.

295
00:13:34,731 --> 00:13:36,483
[INHALES, CLEARS THROAT]

296
00:13:39,120 --> 00:13:40,690
Why... [SIGHS]

297
00:13:42,155 --> 00:13:44,330
... did you go out of
your way to tell Noreen

298
00:13:44,350 --> 00:13:46,159
that the Hampton property was yours?

299
00:13:46,243 --> 00:13:47,244
What?

300
00:13:48,660 --> 00:13:50,620
No, I... I don't know...

301
00:13:51,180 --> 00:13:53,667
- I don't know who Noreen is.
- She was at the party.

302
00:13:53,750 --> 00:13:55,711
The zaftig redhead.

303
00:13:56,660 --> 00:13:58,960
I don't remember saying that to anyone.

304
00:13:58,980 --> 00:14:00,400
Hmm.

305
00:14:00,420 --> 00:14:03,760
Well, you did. She told me.

306
00:14:04,460 --> 00:14:08,240
But what I'm interested
in is why you said it.

307
00:14:08,260 --> 00:14:10,920
Honestly, I-I don't recall
saying that to anyone.

308
00:14:10,930 --> 00:14:12,602
I'm a little disappointed to hear that,

309
00:14:12,610 --> 00:14:15,480
Marty, because I now
know that you're lying.

310
00:14:16,280 --> 00:14:18,400
Noreen recorded the conversation.

311
00:14:19,450 --> 00:14:20,485
She did?

312
00:14:20,500 --> 00:14:21,530
[CHUCKLES]

313
00:14:22,180 --> 00:14:24,150
- Of course she didn't.
- [SIGHS]

314
00:14:24,170 --> 00:14:27,242
What's going on with your
self-esteem, Marty? Hmm?

315
00:14:27,920 --> 00:14:29,820
Why the need to claim things?

316
00:14:29,850 --> 00:14:32,372
It's, uh... It's unbecoming.

317
00:14:32,450 --> 00:14:34,624
What you think you need

318
00:14:34,640 --> 00:14:37,920
to make you look big is in
fact making you look small.

319
00:14:37,940 --> 00:14:40,440
Now, Noreen, she doesn't
know what to think.

320
00:14:40,470 --> 00:14:42,090
And she's... she's worried.

321
00:14:42,540 --> 00:14:44,170
She's worried that you're confused.

322
00:14:44,200 --> 00:14:45,469
So are Bonnie and I.

323
00:14:45,500 --> 00:14:47,930
I'm not, and I... and I didn't
mean to confuse anyone.

324
00:14:47,960 --> 00:14:50,307
I'm just... I'm so... [SIGHS, STAMMERS]

325
00:14:50,390 --> 00:14:51,980
... baffled.

326
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:54,603
It's baffling to me,
Mar... [STAMMERS] Marty.

327
00:14:54,620 --> 00:14:58,190
I... Wh... I mean, why on earth
would you say something like that?

328
00:14:58,210 --> 00:14:59,274
Honestly.

329
00:14:59,850 --> 00:15:01,700
It's my idea to host
these parties, right?

330
00:15:01,720 --> 00:15:03,153
Yeah.

331
00:15:03,170 --> 00:15:07,157
I come up with the... the themes.
I write the invitations.

332
00:15:07,200 --> 00:15:09,117
- I am the host.
- You are.

333
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:12,570
People come to enjoy themselves.

334
00:15:12,663 --> 00:15:15,374
To have fun and relax.

335
00:15:15,400 --> 00:15:17,880
Not be confronted by your...

336
00:15:17,900 --> 00:15:19,500
- pathologies.
- I'm sorry.

337
00:15:19,520 --> 00:15:22,089
I mean, what's the big deal if
they think it's my place, huh?

338
00:15:22,120 --> 00:15:23,632
I mean, who cares whose place it is?

339
00:15:23,715 --> 00:15:24,716
I agree. Totally.

340
00:15:24,760 --> 00:15:27,094
In fact, I-I said to
Noreen afterwards that...

341
00:15:27,120 --> 00:15:29,429
Do you want people to come to
our parties and enjoy themselves,

342
00:15:29,430 --> 00:15:31,973
or do you want them
to feel uncomfortable?

343
00:15:31,974 --> 00:15:34,434
No, I want... I want them
to enjoy themselves.

344
00:15:35,320 --> 00:15:37,770
Do you want to invite people
to take advantage of you?

345
00:15:37,850 --> 00:15:39,940
Hmm? Like Debbie did?

346
00:15:39,960 --> 00:15:41,316
Like Phyllis did?

347
00:15:41,560 --> 00:15:43,943
Cathy, to a certain extent?

348
00:15:43,944 --> 00:15:45,320
No. Of course not.

349
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:47,440
I didn't think so.

350
00:15:49,760 --> 00:15:51,410
You know I'm doing this for you.

351
00:15:52,840 --> 00:15:54,950
To protect you.

352
00:15:55,789 --> 00:15:57,332
We don't care.

353
00:15:57,416 --> 00:15:59,877
But... we're looking out for you.

354
00:15:59,960 --> 00:16:01,712
I know. I know.

355
00:16:01,795 --> 00:16:04,755
So just try not to say those
kinds of things, okay?

356
00:16:04,756 --> 00:16:05,966
Okay.

357
00:16:07,100 --> 00:16:09,130
Again, I'm... I'm so sorry.

358
00:16:09,150 --> 00:16:11,722
And please, tell Bonnie I'm sorry too.

359
00:16:11,750 --> 00:16:13,974
Ah, Marty, I would. I would.

360
00:16:13,990 --> 00:16:17,186
But I'm afraid if I bring
it up to, uh, Bonnie,

361
00:16:17,200 --> 00:16:19,938
she's just going to get
upset all over again.

362
00:16:20,280 --> 00:16:21,480
Oh.

363
00:16:26,380 --> 00:16:27,820
Now...

364
00:16:30,157 --> 00:16:32,074
you know what I'm thinking
for our next theme?

365
00:16:32,075 --> 00:16:33,076
[NEW WAVE MUSIC PLAYING]

366
00:16:33,952 --> 00:16:35,954
Who's ready to walk the plank?

367
00:16:36,038 --> 00:16:37,831
- Aye!
- Amazing.

368
00:16:37,915 --> 00:16:39,916
- Ahoy, Captain.
- [IKE] Right this way, mate.

369
00:16:43,045 --> 00:16:45,043
- You get stage fright now?
- [WOMEN LAUGHING]

370
00:16:45,044 --> 00:16:46,560
"Shiver me timbers."

371
00:16:46,580 --> 00:16:48,299
- You wanna say it?
- [MAN] You got something to say?

372
00:16:48,300 --> 00:16:49,927
- [TWEETS]
- [WOMEN] Aw.

373
00:16:49,940 --> 00:16:51,980
No, he was saying it all morning.

374
00:16:52,000 --> 00:16:53,846
- No...
- [MAN] I think he's gonna do it this time.

375
00:16:53,847 --> 00:16:55,770
You need to change your batteries.

376
00:16:55,790 --> 00:16:57,934
Yeah, you need to change your batteries.

377
00:16:57,935 --> 00:16:59,978
"Shiver me timbers."

378
00:17:00,062 --> 00:17:01,462
[MAN] I don't think it's happening.

379
00:17:01,522 --> 00:17:02,898
[WOMAN LAUGHING]

380
00:17:09,480 --> 00:17:11,420
- More food. [SIGHS]
- [BONNIE] I've had enough.

381
00:17:11,440 --> 00:17:14,992
- No, I meant for the guests.
- I know what you meant. [SNIFFLES]

382
00:17:16,400 --> 00:17:17,950
You okay?

383
00:17:18,000 --> 00:17:20,914
- [SNIFFLES]
- You... You want some water or seltzer?

384
00:17:20,915 --> 00:17:22,626
I miss my husband.

385
00:17:23,980 --> 00:17:25,620
Let me get you a seltzer.

386
00:17:25,660 --> 00:17:28,340
- Remind me. Uh, Perrier or Pellegrino?
- I'm okay.

387
00:17:28,360 --> 00:17:30,920
I... I got both. I'll just
get you a Perrier. Yeah.

388
00:17:30,950 --> 00:17:33,595
Think I read somewhere
that it has less sodium.

389
00:17:33,679 --> 00:17:36,557
And this may sound crazy,
but when I drink Pellegrino,

390
00:17:36,600 --> 00:17:39,768
I think it sometimes makes me
thirstier, if you can believe that.

391
00:17:39,852 --> 00:17:42,229
- There you go.
- Thank you. [SNIFFLES]

392
00:17:43,040 --> 00:17:45,730
Do you remember the first time
we all came here together?

393
00:17:45,740 --> 00:17:48,318
Just us? It was so nice.

394
00:17:48,350 --> 00:17:49,611
It was peaceful.

395
00:17:51,520 --> 00:17:52,820
I do.

396
00:17:53,340 --> 00:17:56,110
- Yeah, it was.
- [SOBBING]

397
00:17:56,201 --> 00:17:57,536
Oh.

398
00:17:58,800 --> 00:18:00,490
It's okay.

399
00:18:00,581 --> 00:18:01,999
[SNIFFLES] I'm sorry.

400
00:18:02,000 --> 00:18:05,544
No. It's okay. It's all right. Yeah.

401
00:18:05,627 --> 00:18:06,920
[SNIFFLING] Okay.

402
00:18:06,950 --> 00:18:11,049
Okay, I jus... I probably... I think
I should, you know, go back

403
00:18:11,050 --> 00:18:12,885
and bring out the extra kebabs.

404
00:18:12,960 --> 00:18:14,600
- Yeah. Okay.
- People are waiting.

405
00:18:14,620 --> 00:18:16,722
- Sorry, Marty.
- No, no, no.

406
00:18:17,380 --> 00:18:19,180
There's also soft drinks in here.

407
00:18:19,266 --> 00:18:21,685
[CRYING] Okay.

408
00:18:21,690 --> 00:18:22,978
- Okay.
- Thank you.

409
00:18:23,061 --> 00:18:25,898
- Uh-huh.
- [GONG CRASHES]

410
00:18:25,981 --> 00:18:27,191
["BUTTONS" PLAYING]

411
00:18:42,664 --> 00:18:45,501
[SONG CONTINUES ON SPEAKERS]

412
00:18:45,584 --> 00:18:48,045
- Pool volleyball?
- Ike, it's too cold.

413
00:18:48,080 --> 00:18:50,100
You don't happen to have
another towel, do you?

414
00:18:50,120 --> 00:18:52,382
Or, maybe, I don't know,
like, a light blanket?

415
00:18:52,780 --> 00:18:57,420
You... Uh, no, uh...
I'll... I'll ask Bonnie.

416
00:18:59,440 --> 00:19:02,100
Hey, Ike. What time's
the bus leaving tonight?

417
00:19:02,120 --> 00:19:04,102
[SIGHS] I'm... I'm kinda done.

418
00:19:04,186 --> 00:19:07,689
- Arthur, have a drink. It's a party.
- [GROANS]

419
00:19:08,320 --> 00:19:10,730
Ah, what the hell. [CHUCKLES]

420
00:19:10,817 --> 00:19:12,736
I'll take an English breakfast tea.

421
00:19:12,819 --> 00:19:13,820
Tea?

422
00:19:14,900 --> 00:19:16,320
Anything in it?

423
00:19:16,700 --> 00:19:18,950
Little steamed milk would be nice.

424
00:19:21,700 --> 00:19:23,700
pH level is good.

425
00:19:24,640 --> 00:19:26,200
Here we are.

426
00:19:27,340 --> 00:19:28,620
Here we go.

427
00:19:29,300 --> 00:19:32,540
All right. Yes. Enough for everyone.

428
00:19:32,631 --> 00:19:34,967
Oh, come on, bud. You gotta share.

429
00:19:35,050 --> 00:19:37,220
Stop that. [SIGHS]

430
00:19:37,250 --> 00:19:38,720
There you are.

431
00:19:38,804 --> 00:19:43,475
Looks like your <i>Ichthyophthirius
multifiliis</i> is finally clearing up.

432
00:19:43,559 --> 00:19:46,520
Those formula drops
are working. Attaboy.

433
00:19:46,880 --> 00:19:49,140
Look at you. Your scales are so lush.

434
00:19:49,231 --> 00:19:50,858
[IKE] Who are you talking to?

435
00:19:50,880 --> 00:19:52,651
Oh, you scared me.

436
00:19:53,060 --> 00:19:54,770
Y... You're talking to the fish?

437
00:19:56,380 --> 00:19:57,860
Yeah, I guess.

438
00:20:00,340 --> 00:20:01,780
Hey, guess who, uh...

439
00:20:02,820 --> 00:20:05,830
Guess who's nominated to be
vice president of the temple.

440
00:20:06,640 --> 00:20:09,410
Wow, congratulations.

441
00:20:09,501 --> 00:20:11,378
Why don't you come back to the party?

442
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:14,100
Michael's friend from Los
Angeles is gonna tell us

443
00:20:14,120 --> 00:20:17,217
about the time he went hiking with
Craig T. Nelson from <i>Coach</i>.

444
00:20:17,250 --> 00:20:18,969
Oh, yeah, from <i>Coach</i>. Yeah.

445
00:20:19,600 --> 00:20:23,050
No, yeah, I-I'll be back soon.
I gotta flip the kebabs anyway.

446
00:20:23,557 --> 00:20:25,642
[MUSIC CONTINUES IN DISTANCE]

447
00:20:28,280 --> 00:20:30,890
You know, Marty,

448
00:20:31,860 --> 00:20:34,480
these parties are... are for us.

449
00:20:34,500 --> 00:20:35,694
For both of us.

450
00:20:36,260 --> 00:20:41,700
I... I can't have fun if
you're not right by my side.

451
00:20:44,440 --> 00:20:46,537
Not that this is much of a party anyway.

452
00:20:49,760 --> 00:20:51,160
Here.

453
00:20:51,180 --> 00:20:52,794
[GROANS] No, thanks.

454
00:20:52,810 --> 00:20:55,129
My... My reflux is acting up.

455
00:20:55,130 --> 00:20:57,007
Oh, come on. It's one beer.

456
00:20:57,700 --> 00:20:58,880
To us.

457
00:21:00,040 --> 00:21:01,340
Okay.

458
00:21:07,440 --> 00:21:09,640
- Refreshing.
- Come on. Drink it.

459
00:21:09,728 --> 00:21:12,606
- Give it a real sip.
- [STAMMERS] That was a real sip.

460
00:21:12,689 --> 00:21:15,192
No, come on. We need to see Party Marty.

461
00:21:15,275 --> 00:21:16,276
The crowd wants it.

462
00:21:16,360 --> 00:21:19,362
Party Marty has a migraine, okay?
I think it's from the sun.

463
00:21:21,380 --> 00:21:23,616
You know this is part
of our work, Marty.

464
00:21:23,617 --> 00:21:26,245
I... I want you to be free.

465
00:21:26,270 --> 00:21:28,080
I want you to fly.

466
00:21:31,000 --> 00:21:32,830
There we go. Oh, yes.

467
00:21:32,918 --> 00:21:35,587
[CHANTING] Party Marty. Party Marty!

468
00:21:35,671 --> 00:21:39,383
Yes! Yes! There he is!

469
00:21:39,410 --> 00:21:42,719
- There we go.
- Whoa. Whew!

470
00:21:42,750 --> 00:21:43,804
Oh, my God.

471
00:21:43,887 --> 00:21:46,807
- That is fantastic. Here.
- What? Oh.

472
00:21:46,820 --> 00:21:50,561
Now you can enjoy yourself.
Now you can loosen up, be free.

473
00:21:50,644 --> 00:21:52,187
[SIGHS]

474
00:21:52,271 --> 00:21:54,731
[SIGHS] Look at this place, oy.

475
00:21:55,315 --> 00:21:57,776
You know what I think would
get this party really started?

476
00:21:57,860 --> 00:21:59,960
- What?
- If everyone started jumping in the pool

477
00:21:59,970 --> 00:22:00,987
with their clothes on.

478
00:22:00,988 --> 00:22:03,407
- [LAUGHS]
- Could you imagine? [CHUCKLES]

479
00:22:03,420 --> 00:22:06,410
- That would be... Yeah. [LAUGHS]
- You should start it.

480
00:22:06,493 --> 00:22:07,578
- Me?
- Yeah!

481
00:22:07,661 --> 00:22:10,289
- I don't know. No.
- I do! I do.

482
00:22:10,372 --> 00:22:12,082
- Come here. Look at Miriam.
- Hmm?

483
00:22:15,440 --> 00:22:17,753
You know, you should
just go nudge her in.

484
00:22:18,240 --> 00:22:20,480
- Why... Into the pool?
- She would love it.

485
00:22:20,500 --> 00:22:23,093
- She's such a prankster.
- Really? I-I didn't know that.

486
00:22:23,170 --> 00:22:25,320
Oh, if you only knew
some of the high jinks

487
00:22:25,350 --> 00:22:26,972
she's been a part of, oy...

488
00:22:27,055 --> 00:22:28,557
She likes high jinks, huh?

489
00:22:28,640 --> 00:22:31,143
She will think it's hilarious.
She loves you.

490
00:22:32,060 --> 00:22:34,730
Party Marty. Party Marty.

491
00:22:34,813 --> 00:22:38,400
Party Marty. Party Mar... [CHUCKLES]

492
00:22:44,680 --> 00:22:46,150
[MARTY] Hey, Miriam.

493
00:22:46,170 --> 00:22:47,500
Oh, hey, Marty. [LAUGHS]

494
00:22:47,520 --> 00:22:49,620
Wow, where have you been? [SCREAMS]

495
00:22:49,703 --> 00:22:51,997
[PARTY GUESTS GASP]

496
00:22:55,125 --> 00:22:56,418
[MURMURING]

497
00:22:57,280 --> 00:22:59,040
What the fuck are you doing?

498
00:22:59,129 --> 00:23:00,839
I... I'm sorry.

499
00:23:00,850 --> 00:23:02,716
I-I thought it would be funny!

500
00:23:02,799 --> 00:23:04,426
Why would this be funny, Marty?

501
00:23:04,510 --> 00:23:06,670
- [WOMAN] That was crazy.
- The fuck is wrong with you?

502
00:23:07,400 --> 00:23:09,050
- [MARTY] Are you all right?
- No.

503
00:23:11,642 --> 00:23:14,394
[GROANS] Are you insane? You... [SOBS]

504
00:23:15,187 --> 00:23:16,980
Guess I-I just got carried away.

505
00:23:17,648 --> 00:23:19,650
Ike gave me a bunch of beers.

506
00:23:19,680 --> 00:23:21,460
Well... Wait, Marty, no.

507
00:23:21,480 --> 00:23:24,279
What I said was it would be fun
if everyone went swimming.

508
00:23:24,363 --> 00:23:26,323
I didn't say to body check her.

509
00:23:26,350 --> 00:23:28,825
Look, I-I-I'm very sorry.
He misread the situation.

510
00:23:28,909 --> 00:23:32,286
I-I normally don't drink,
you know? All that alcohol.

511
00:23:32,287 --> 00:23:34,623
Well, guess what, Marty.
I got news for you.

512
00:23:34,640 --> 00:23:37,334
You're okay. That beer was nonalcoholic.

513
00:23:37,417 --> 00:23:39,002
- What?
- Yeah.

514
00:23:39,380 --> 00:23:43,169
Why would you? Wh... Why...
Why would... Why would you...

515
00:23:43,170 --> 00:23:46,140
Because Party Marty is in here.

516
00:23:46,160 --> 00:23:47,386
You just need to let go.

517
00:23:47,400 --> 00:23:50,848
Now, admittedly, this was
a little over-the-top.

518
00:23:50,860 --> 00:23:53,684
Yeah, it's a work in progress.
Why don't you take care of her?

519
00:23:56,420 --> 00:24:00,310
It's a party. [LAUGHS] Pool's open.

520
00:24:00,399 --> 00:24:02,484
Miriam, look, I-I'm
sorry. Le-Let's get...

521
00:24:02,568 --> 00:24:04,736
Just go away, Marty. I don't
need your fucking help.

522
00:24:04,770 --> 00:24:06,238
Oh, no, you're crying.

523
00:24:06,280 --> 00:24:08,824
- It's fine. It isn't your fault, okay?
- Well, it is.

524
00:24:08,850 --> 00:24:10,742
No, it isn't. It's fucking Ike, okay?

525
00:24:10,760 --> 00:24:13,660
He put you up to this. I don't know
why you listened to him, but...

526
00:24:13,680 --> 00:24:15,289
[SOBS]

527
00:24:15,300 --> 00:24:17,040
... it isn't your fault.

528
00:24:17,880 --> 00:24:21,710
Oh, God. You know, I didn't even
want to come to this stupid thing.

529
00:24:21,720 --> 00:24:23,839
I shouldn't have.
I should have known better.

530
00:24:23,850 --> 00:24:26,132
You didn't know I was gonna
push you in the pool.

531
00:24:26,133 --> 00:24:27,718
No, I did not know that.

532
00:24:29,840 --> 00:24:32,460
But I know Ike's an asshole. [SOBBING]

533
00:24:32,480 --> 00:24:35,058
And I know that I am done
with him. I am done!

534
00:24:38,620 --> 00:24:40,563
Did you know that my mother died?

535
00:24:40,564 --> 00:24:42,065
I'm so sorry.

536
00:24:42,140 --> 00:24:44,140
[SNIFFLES] It's okay.
It happened years ago.

537
00:24:44,150 --> 00:24:46,580
But my mother died, and
Ike fucking convinced me

538
00:24:46,590 --> 00:24:47,905
to stop talking to her.

539
00:24:47,988 --> 00:24:50,115
Just to stop talking to her.

540
00:24:50,130 --> 00:24:51,825
Just completely cut her off.

541
00:24:54,828 --> 00:24:57,039
So I never got to say goodbye to her.

542
00:24:59,833 --> 00:25:01,460
My own mother, I just...

543
00:25:02,260 --> 00:25:04,750
Who fucking does that? Who does that?

544
00:25:07,320 --> 00:25:10,380
- Let's get you into some dry clothes.
- Okay. [SOBBING CONTINUES]

545
00:25:11,011 --> 00:25:12,804
- Okay.
- Okay. [SOBS]

546
00:25:14,440 --> 00:25:16,600
It was a new dress!

547
00:25:16,620 --> 00:25:19,478
- [MARTY] I'm sorry. I just...
- [SNIFFLES]

548
00:25:22,320 --> 00:25:24,230
Miriam, you doing all right in there?

549
00:25:28,190 --> 00:25:30,738
- I don't think I need the hat.
- You may.

550
00:25:30,740 --> 00:25:33,033
It really helps, you know,
keep the sun out of your eyes.

551
00:25:33,070 --> 00:25:35,452
- You should try it.
- [CHUCKLES]

552
00:25:36,540 --> 00:25:38,450
Um... [CLEARS THROAT]

553
00:25:38,480 --> 00:25:41,708
I felt bad I got water all over
the floor. Is there a mop?

554
00:25:41,792 --> 00:25:44,419
I don't... I don't wanna leave
the housekeeper's room a mess.

555
00:25:44,430 --> 00:25:46,713
Oh, this isn't the
housekeeper's room. It's mine.

556
00:25:47,214 --> 00:25:48,382
What?

557
00:25:49,900 --> 00:25:51,380
Yeah.

558
00:25:51,780 --> 00:25:54,170
This is where you sleep?

559
00:25:54,680 --> 00:25:56,230
This is where I sleep.

560
00:25:56,265 --> 00:25:59,434
This is my bed. These are my shells.

561
00:25:59,450 --> 00:26:01,936
My sandpiper painting.
I got my fridge over there.

562
00:26:01,937 --> 00:26:02,960
[CHUCKLES]

563
00:26:02,980 --> 00:26:06,275
- D-Do you wanna go back to the party?
- Not particularly, no.

564
00:26:08,420 --> 00:26:11,020
[SIGHS] What is it
about that man, right?

565
00:26:11,050 --> 00:26:14,241
Well, he's, um... He's complicated.

566
00:26:15,420 --> 00:26:16,860
But he cares.

567
00:26:18,040 --> 00:26:19,450
I used to think that.

568
00:26:20,320 --> 00:26:22,488
I used to think that he cared about me.

569
00:26:22,500 --> 00:26:23,550
[EXHALES SHAKILY]

570
00:26:24,440 --> 00:26:27,040
He was my everything. Do you
know that I actually loved him?

571
00:26:28,280 --> 00:26:30,040
But he broke my heart.

572
00:26:30,132 --> 00:26:33,260
Because he doesn't...
care about me at all.

573
00:26:33,343 --> 00:26:35,012
He doesn't care about any of us.

574
00:26:35,040 --> 00:26:38,223
I don't know the specifics of
what you two have going on,

575
00:26:39,180 --> 00:26:41,310
but with us, it's different, okay?

576
00:26:41,600 --> 00:26:44,140
He cares about me, I can assure you.

577
00:26:44,170 --> 00:26:46,523
He loves me. He changed my life.

578
00:26:46,860 --> 00:26:49,400
- He's my best friend.
- Do you hear yourself right now?

579
00:26:49,484 --> 00:26:52,070
A journey of self-discovery
isn't easy, Miriam.

580
00:26:52,100 --> 00:26:54,323
But don't blame Ike for your own shit.

581
00:26:54,406 --> 00:26:56,283
Ike saved me. Do you understand?

582
00:26:56,366 --> 00:26:59,536
I owe my life to him.
I would be dead without Ike.

583
00:26:59,580 --> 00:27:01,079
100% dead.

584
00:27:02,480 --> 00:27:04,040
I owe him everything.

585
00:27:04,124 --> 00:27:05,250
Wow.

586
00:27:06,500 --> 00:27:07,790
You're in real deep, huh?

587
00:27:07,878 --> 00:27:09,379
[IKE] Everything okay in here?

588
00:27:09,463 --> 00:27:10,923
- Uh... Oh, yeah.
- Uh, yeah.

589
00:27:10,940 --> 00:27:14,801
Just, uh, helping Miriam, you know,
find some... some dry clothes.

590
00:27:15,302 --> 00:27:16,470
Ah.

591
00:27:17,740 --> 00:27:19,430
You look good in green, Miriam.

592
00:27:20,690 --> 00:27:21,724
Thanks.

593
00:27:21,725 --> 00:27:24,895
So sorry to barge in. Honey,
Carl wants to duet with you.

594
00:27:24,930 --> 00:27:27,460
Oh, no. Don't tell me you
broke out the karaoke machine.

595
00:27:27,480 --> 00:27:28,860
I'm guilty as charged.

596
00:27:28,880 --> 00:27:30,440
It's out, it's on,

597
00:27:30,460 --> 00:27:32,776
and it is primed with "Fight
for Your Right to Party."

598
00:27:32,778 --> 00:27:34,029
[IKE] Oh, do I have to?

599
00:27:34,040 --> 00:27:35,500
He's taking us to the opening night

600
00:27:35,520 --> 00:27:37,032
of the New York City Ballet, okay?

601
00:27:37,040 --> 00:27:39,475
- Nothing comes for free. [LAUGHS]
- No, you've got a point.

602
00:27:39,535 --> 00:27:42,239
Okay, come here. Mmm.
Oh, do you two want to sing?

603
00:27:42,240 --> 00:27:43,704
Actually, you know what, Marty?

604
00:27:43,710 --> 00:27:45,069
I need you to grab me something, okay?

605
00:27:45,070 --> 00:27:47,334
We're out of limes, and
the people need margaritas.

606
00:27:47,417 --> 00:27:49,795
- Can you handle?
- I... I'm on it.

607
00:27:49,878 --> 00:27:51,672
Thanks, Marty. Come
on, come on, come on.

608
00:28:20,380 --> 00:28:22,610
Marty? Marty Markowitz?

609
00:28:23,220 --> 00:28:25,240
Yes. Mrs. Zicherman.

610
00:28:25,330 --> 00:28:27,374
I-I thought you moved.

611
00:28:27,390 --> 00:28:29,293
No... [SIGHS] No. No.

612
00:28:29,560 --> 00:28:31,620
Oh. Well, I-I...

613
00:28:31,650 --> 00:28:34,171
The, um, mailbox had a different name,

614
00:28:34,173 --> 00:28:36,133
and I thought you left
without saying goodbye.

615
00:28:36,216 --> 00:28:38,844
[CHUCKLES] No,
I-I-I'm still there. Yeah.

616
00:28:38,880 --> 00:28:42,806
Oh, okay. Well... [CHUCKLES]
What are you up to?

617
00:28:42,820 --> 00:28:45,350
- [CHUCKLES] How's Phyllis?
- Um...

618
00:28:45,380 --> 00:28:48,227
Oh, I heard Nancy had a little girl.

619
00:28:48,228 --> 00:28:51,815
- You must be over the moon.
- Really?

620
00:28:51,830 --> 00:28:54,050
Yeah, I got a, um...
a birth announcement.

621
00:28:54,080 --> 00:28:55,776
- Ah, what a cute name.
- Uh-huh.

622
00:28:56,920 --> 00:28:58,400
And how's Joel?

623
00:28:59,400 --> 00:29:00,650
Um...

624
00:29:02,200 --> 00:29:05,320
- Are you okay?
- Yeah. No, I'm fine.

625
00:29:05,350 --> 00:29:07,998
I'm just, uh, here to, you know,
pick up some essentials.

626
00:29:08,600 --> 00:29:09,750
Some limes.

627
00:29:09,770 --> 00:29:11,520
Uh, you look a little pale.

628
00:29:11,540 --> 00:29:13,420
Uh, just tired, I think. Yeah.

629
00:29:13,504 --> 00:29:16,673
[CHUCKLES] Well, it's
really good to see you.

630
00:29:16,690 --> 00:29:18,509
- Yeah, likewise. Yeah. Uh-huh.
- Yeah.

631
00:29:18,590 --> 00:29:20,520
I-I-I-I mean, I've been
thinking about you a lot.

632
00:29:20,540 --> 00:29:23,430
- Oh?
- Um, so I'm glad you're okay.

633
00:29:23,514 --> 00:29:24,515
Yes.

634
00:29:25,320 --> 00:29:28,120
Hey, um, why don't you bring Phyllis

635
00:29:28,140 --> 00:29:30,686
and the kids over next time they're out?

636
00:29:30,687 --> 00:29:32,814
We'll all catch up. It'll be wonderful.

637
00:29:32,840 --> 00:29:34,034
I haven't seen them in years,

638
00:29:34,035 --> 00:29:35,941
so there's a lot to catch
up on. [CHUCKLES]

639
00:29:35,942 --> 00:29:38,900
- Okay, well, um...
- Okay.

640
00:29:38,987 --> 00:29:41,323
- Well, good to see you. I'll see you.
- Yeah. Oh.

641
00:29:42,150 --> 00:29:43,490
- All right.
- [CHUCKLES]

642
00:29:43,500 --> 00:29:45,702
- Bye-bye. Yeah.
- Bye-bye.

643
00:30:01,885 --> 00:30:03,846
[TIRES SCREECH]

644
00:30:04,680 --> 00:30:06,765
- [CAR HORN HONKS]
- [BREATHING HEAVILY]

645
00:30:24,449 --> 00:30:25,701
[EXHALES]

646
00:30:35,878 --> 00:30:37,588
[TIRES SCREECH]

647
00:30:45,095 --> 00:30:48,182
- Please, stop! I...
- [TIRES SCREECH]

648
00:30:48,200 --> 00:30:50,600
- I'm sorry. Stop.
- [MAN] What the hell?

649
00:30:50,620 --> 00:30:52,300
- Just hold on.
- Watch where you're going.

650
00:30:52,895 --> 00:30:54,897
[BREATHING HEAVILY]

651
00:31:00,986 --> 00:31:02,236
- [TIRES SCREECH]
- [HONKING]

652
00:31:02,237 --> 00:31:05,032
Fuck! [SIGHS]

653
00:31:05,115 --> 00:31:06,491
[CAR HORN HONKS]

654
00:31:07,159 --> 00:31:09,286
- [TIRES SQUEAL]
- [MAN] Asshole!

655
00:31:20,297 --> 00:31:23,550
[RADIO: 1950S POP MUSIC PLAYING]

656
00:31:25,480 --> 00:31:27,130
Where are you going, Marty?

657
00:31:28,640 --> 00:31:30,340
Come back, sweetheart.

658
00:31:30,360 --> 00:31:32,351
One more spoon for Mama.

659
00:31:33,780 --> 00:31:35,100
[ECHOING] Come on.

660
00:31:36,340 --> 00:31:39,080
That's it. That's my good boy.

661
00:31:40,240 --> 00:31:41,280
Well done.

662
00:31:41,401 --> 00:31:43,111
[MUSIC FADES]

663
00:31:43,195 --> 00:31:45,322
[NO AUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

664
00:31:45,405 --> 00:31:48,242
[PARTY GUESTS LAUGHING, MUFFLED]

665
00:32:06,468 --> 00:32:07,553
[SIGHS]

666
00:32:39,459 --> 00:32:41,545
[PARTY GUESTS LAUGHING,
CHATTERING IN DISTANCE]

667
00:32:42,680 --> 00:32:44,210
How you doing, pal?

668
00:32:45,020 --> 00:32:47,420
You... Are you okay?

669
00:32:47,440 --> 00:32:50,846
You want some Tylenol?
Some... Some water or some...

670
00:32:51,760 --> 00:32:53,970
You know, I've been looking
for you for ages. It...

671
00:32:54,000 --> 00:32:55,684
People have been asking for you.

672
00:33:05,402 --> 00:33:06,778
[GRUNTS]

673
00:33:09,580 --> 00:33:10,614
Hi, friend.

674
00:33:14,300 --> 00:33:15,452
Tell me their names.

675
00:33:16,300 --> 00:33:17,830
- Really?
- Mmm.

676
00:33:19,360 --> 00:33:20,950
Um...

677
00:33:21,000 --> 00:33:23,378
That's Stu. And he's Ethan.

678
00:33:23,680 --> 00:33:26,350
Sass is the one eating all
the... the plants over there.

679
00:33:26,370 --> 00:33:27,800
- [CHUCKLES]
- And that's Catheryn.

680
00:33:27,820 --> 00:33:29,843
She's kind of demure. [CHUCKLES]

681
00:33:29,927 --> 00:33:31,929
Don't... Don't look at her too long.

682
00:33:31,950 --> 00:33:36,099
And, uh... And that's Adam.
He is not doing so well recently.

683
00:33:38,519 --> 00:33:40,270
They're lucky they have you.

684
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:43,190
You think?

685
00:33:43,480 --> 00:33:45,060
I know.

686
00:33:49,620 --> 00:33:53,400
So, what are you planning next?
What's your next big project?

687
00:33:54,240 --> 00:33:59,450
I don't know. I was thinking...
maybe some bees.

688
00:33:59,540 --> 00:34:00,916
That would be wonderful.

689
00:34:00,999 --> 00:34:02,334
[CHATTERING, LAUGHING CONTINUES]

690
00:34:02,417 --> 00:34:03,710
[CHUCKLES]

691
00:34:06,980 --> 00:34:09,880
I'm... I'm thinking I might
go back into the city tonight.

692
00:34:09,967 --> 00:34:11,260
Are you sure?

693
00:34:12,080 --> 00:34:13,970
Yeah, I'm not feeling so great.

694
00:34:14,760 --> 00:34:17,510
Okay. Seems a shame, but...

695
00:34:19,520 --> 00:34:22,560
No, I... Of course.

696
00:34:30,320 --> 00:34:31,737
[DRIPPING]

697
00:34:31,740 --> 00:34:33,657
Oh, hey, Marty,

698
00:34:34,360 --> 00:34:37,200
if you're going back
to the city tonight,

699
00:34:37,840 --> 00:34:39,240
could you do me a favor?

700
00:34:40,140 --> 00:34:41,740
Yeah, sure.

701
00:34:42,290 --> 00:34:46,520
["I WANT TO KNOW WHAT LOVE
IS" PLAYING ON SPEAKERS]

702
00:34:49,120 --> 00:34:53,050
[PARTY GUESTS] <i>♪ I want you to show me ♪</i>

703
00:34:54,820 --> 00:34:58,880
<i>♪ I wanna feel what love is ♪</i>

704
00:35:01,140 --> 00:35:06,320
<i>♪ I know you can show me ♪</i>

705
00:35:07,600 --> 00:35:09,860
<i>♪ Oh ♪</i>

706
00:35:09,943 --> 00:35:11,778
[MUSIC CRACKLES, STOPS]

707
00:35:11,790 --> 00:35:14,143
- [ARTHUR] What just happened?
- [DRIVER] It's overheated.

708
00:35:17,492 --> 00:35:19,035
- [WOMAN 1] Are we stranded?
- [WOMAN 2] Call for help.

709
00:35:19,036 --> 00:35:21,019
- [WOMAN 3] We're stranded? What?
- [PARTY GUESTS CLAMORING]

710
00:35:21,020 --> 00:35:24,840
- I, uh... I got no cell service.
- [WOMAN 3] Does anyone have service?

711
00:35:24,860 --> 00:35:26,069
- Um...
- [WOMAN 4] You don't have any?

712
00:35:26,070 --> 00:35:28,630
All right, everyone.
Relax. It's gonna be okay.

713
00:35:28,670 --> 00:35:31,460
Th-There's a gas station down the road.

714
00:35:31,480 --> 00:35:33,382
I-I'll go ahead and walk down there

715
00:35:33,390 --> 00:35:36,120
and make a call for help, all right?

716
00:35:36,140 --> 00:35:38,304
- [WOMAN 5] Can you see anything?
- [PARTY GUESTS MURMURING]

717
00:35:38,305 --> 00:35:40,224
- Uh... Miriam?
- What?

718
00:35:40,307 --> 00:35:44,269
Would you, uh... Would
you mind walking with me?

719
00:35:44,353 --> 00:35:46,355
I feel like I owe you an apology.

720
00:35:51,260 --> 00:35:52,730
You're lucky I have to pee.

721
00:35:53,540 --> 00:35:54,860
Thanks.

722
00:35:56,156 --> 00:35:58,033
[BUS DOOR OPENS]

723
00:35:58,116 --> 00:36:01,537
Watch... Watch out for this mud here.

724
00:36:01,820 --> 00:36:04,450
- Thanks.
- There we go.

725
00:36:04,920 --> 00:36:06,450
[MARTY SIGHS]

726
00:36:06,480 --> 00:36:09,210
You know, I ju... I just wanted
to say that, uh... [SIGHS]

727
00:36:09,230 --> 00:36:13,380
I'm... I'm sorry for earlier
when I... I lost my temper.

728
00:36:14,240 --> 00:36:16,800
[SIGHS] It's okay. I understand.

729
00:36:17,120 --> 00:36:18,720
No, i-it's not okay.

730
00:36:18,750 --> 00:36:21,932
I mean, you must've
struck a chord, I guess,

731
00:36:21,960 --> 00:36:24,017
but, uh, I shouldn't
have shouted like that.

732
00:36:26,220 --> 00:36:28,230
It's fine. Really.

733
00:36:29,540 --> 00:36:31,880
It's hard to hear a truth like that.

734
00:36:34,020 --> 00:36:38,240
I mean, I'm... [SIGHS] still
struggling with it myself.

735
00:36:39,500 --> 00:36:42,240
Just keep thinking what my
life would be like if...

736
00:36:42,840 --> 00:36:45,060
I just never met him, you know?

737
00:36:45,860 --> 00:36:46,990
Yeah.

738
00:36:50,836 --> 00:36:51,879
[MIRIAM SIGHS]

739
00:36:53,180 --> 00:36:54,780
I'm just gonna go use the restroom.

740
00:36:54,800 --> 00:36:56,341
- Yeah, sure.
- Okay.

741
00:36:58,200 --> 00:36:59,840
- [DOOR OPENS]
- [DOOR SENSOR CHIMES]

742
00:36:59,928 --> 00:37:01,263
[COINS JINGLING]

743
00:37:06,351 --> 00:37:08,854
- [DIAL TONE]
- [COIN SLOT RATTLES]

744
00:37:08,937 --> 00:37:12,232
[PHONE BEEPING]

745
00:37:12,316 --> 00:37:14,318
[LINE RINGS]

746
00:37:24,520 --> 00:37:25,700
Thanks.

747
00:37:27,122 --> 00:37:28,790
[DOOR SENSOR CHIMES]

748
00:37:31,840 --> 00:37:33,210
Marty?

749
00:37:35,960 --> 00:37:38,880
- Marty?
- [PHONE RINGING]

750
00:37:54,180 --> 00:37:56,150
- Hello?
- [IKE] <i>Hello, Miriam.</i>

751
00:37:56,620 --> 00:37:59,900
<i>I'm afraid to say I won't be able
to be your therapist anymore.</i>

752
00:37:59,920 --> 00:38:02,700
<i>I no longer think this
is a healthy arrangement.</i>

753
00:38:02,720 --> 00:38:05,410
<i>I think you're a very toxic person,</i>

754
00:38:05,430 --> 00:38:07,412
<i>and I don't wanna hear from you again.</i>

755
00:38:07,430 --> 00:38:08,497
- Ike!
- <i>Goodbye.</i>

756
00:38:08,580 --> 00:38:11,041
- [LINE CLICKS, BEEPING]
- Ike, what's going on?

757
00:38:11,124 --> 00:38:13,377
[PANTING]

758
00:38:24,721 --> 00:38:26,849
[GRUNTS, BREATHING HEAVILY]

759
00:38:32,688 --> 00:38:34,982
- [EXHALES DEEPLY]
- [BUS DOOR CLOSES]

760
00:38:35,065 --> 00:38:36,733
- [ENGINE STARTS]
- [SIGHS]

761
00:38:36,817 --> 00:38:39,403
- ["I WANT TO KNOW WHAT LOVE IS" RESUMES]
- [EXHALES DEEPLY]

762
00:38:41,029 --> 00:38:43,282
[ENGINE REVS]

763
00:38:51,748 --> 00:38:53,584
[SONG CONTINUES]

764
00:39:04,460 --> 00:39:05,970
Thanks, Mike.

765
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:09,099
I know that was, uh, unusual.

766
00:39:13,260 --> 00:39:15,640
Don't ever ask me to do that shit again.

767
00:39:19,443 --> 00:39:22,529
[SONG CONTINUES]

768
00:39:37,878 --> 00:39:40,422
[SONG CONTINUES]

769
00:41:26,486 --> 00:41:29,823
[SONG FADES]
